Analyze Heading Structure

01
On this page
  1. Visually Analyze the Listing Detail Page Structure
  2. Highlight Headings with Accessibility Insights
  3. Analyze Heading Structure with Web Developer Toolbar
  4. Heading Structure Matters

There can be a marriage between visual style and the underlying structure of the page, but no matter how it looks we have to ensure we use proper semantic markup.

Let's take a peek under the hood of the Listing Detail page to see its current structure and find opportunities for improvement.

Visually Analyze the Listing Detail Page Structure

From the get-go, it is apparent that there is visual structure to the page.

Up at the top is a site header and MegaNav that includes a logo and links to other places on the site.

Below is the location’s title, along with a description, amenities, and calendar.

All of these look like good pieces of content to form the basis for a heading structure.

We’ll keep these elements in mind as we continue analyzing the page.

Highlight Headings with Accessibility Insights

One tool I lean on when building with accessibility in mind is the Accessibility Insights extension for Chrome (and Edge).

Install the extension, then navigate to the Cranberry Lake listing detail page in your local dev environment. Once the page is loaded, click the blue heart icon button in the Chrome toolbar to open “Accessibility Insights for Web”.

There is a lot of functionality to Accessibility Insights but for now we’ll work with the “Ad hoc tools”.

From there, you will find a series of toggles. Switch on the Headings tool to see the representation of headings present on the page.

Despite the number of content candidates we identified earlier, the only headings present on the page are three H2s in the MegaMenu and an H4 for the month in the date picker.

Analyze Heading Structure with Web Developer Toolbar

Another tool that I use for assessing the heading structure of a page is Web Developer Toolbar. This is another browser extension available for Chrome and Firefox. Once installed, you can open the extension by clicking its gear icon in the browser extensions area next to the address bar.

This extension has lots of functionality with varied usefulness, but for now, we will use its “View Document Outline” feature. (Note: It sure would be awesome if browsers had a built-in heading outline visualizer.)

The resulting information from Web Developer’s View Document Outline tool shows us every heading in the page’s markup (not just those currently rendered on-screen) as well as their structure.

Running this tool confirms what we already knew. Our heading markup isn’t structured as well as it should be to describe the content in a screen reader friendly outline.

Almost all the headings we see are in the MegaNav, which works fine for that part of the page structure, but the page is missing an H1. In addition, it appears that the date picker’s H4 of August 2022 appears to be nested under a heading in the MegaNav.

Since the current structure of the headings doesn’t match the page’s true content hierarchy, someone using a screen reader who can’t see the screen won’t have as good of an experience as they should.

Heading Structure Matters

Through regular use of both Web Developer Toolbar and Accessibility Insights as part of a testing process, you’ll find that each tool has its strengths and weaknesses (including some corner cases affecting accuracy). I suggest using both tools, but be sure to test your pages with Assistive Technology for the final say.

It’s much easier for screen reader users to get an idea for your page’s content and navigate its sections when a semantic heading structure is in place.
